{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AFp4fFrvdvKzwoB5w242wE","type":"tool_result","content":"     1вҶ’# Iteration 18 вҖ” Failure Analysis\n     2вҶ’\n     3вҶ’## Overview\n     4вҶ’\n     5вҶ’54 failures out of 203 test cases (73% pass rate). The failures cluster into 8 distinct root-cause patterns. Most failures involve one of two dominant issues: **ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatch** (algorithm faithfully returns OCR casing but test expects canonical mixed case) and **OCR garbage prologue that bypasses burst detection** (long garbage lines sneak through and beat the real title). Several other structural bugs account for the remainder.\n     6вҶ’\n     7вҶ’---\n     8вҶ’\n     9вҶ’## Pattern 1: ALL_CAPS Title in OCR, Mixed-Case Expected (largest group, ~20 failures)\n    10вҶ’\n    11вҶ’**Affected files:** Barszcz, Beef Stew, Mushroom Pasta, Mushroom Barley Soup, Kluski ЕҡlД…skie, Pierogi Ruskie, Placki Serowe, Placki Ziemniaczane, Placki Owocowe, Placki SЕӮodkie, Roladki Szpinakowe, Paella Valenciana, Chocolate Brownies + Fudgy Chocolate Brownies, and others.\n    12вҶ’\n    13вҶ’**What the OCR has:** The recipe title is in ALL_CAPS (e.g., `BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`, `MUSHROOM PASTA`, `PLACKI SEROWE`).\n    14вҶ’\n    15вҶ’**What the algorithm returns:** The verbatim OCR string in ALL_CAPS (e.g., `BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`).\n    16вҶ’\n    17вҶ’**What the test expects:** Title-cased string (e.g., `Barszcz`, `Beef Stew`, `Placki Serowe`).\n    18вҶ’\n    19вҶ’**Why it fails:** The algorithm has no case normalization step. It returns text exactly as it appears in the OCR. Tests that have ALL_CAPS expectations (e.g., `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA`, `ARAYES SHRAK`) pass because the expected string matches the OCR. Tests with Title Case expectations fail because the expected string differs in case.\n    20вҶ’\n    21вҶ’**Concrete trace вҖ” Barszcz:**\n    22вҶ’```\n    23вҶ’File line 1: BARSZCZ\n    24вҶ’Expected:    Barszcz\n    25вҶ’Got:         BARSZCZ\n    26вҶ’```\n    27вҶ’`BARSZCZ` is a valid single-word structural candidate. It passes all hard filters and scores well for recipe title. The algorithm returns it faithfully. The test fails on a string-equality comparison.\n    28вҶ’\n    29вҶ’**Concrete trace вҖ” Paella Valenciana:**\n    30вҶ’```\n    31вҶ’File line 1: PAELLA\n    32вҶ’File line 2: VALENCIANA\n    33вҶ’```\n    34вҶ’Both are ALL_CAPS single-word lines (вүӨ2 words, вүӨ25 chars). The caps-coalescing logic correctly merges them into `PAELLA VALENCIANA`. But expected is `Paella Valenciana`. Case mismatch.\n    35вҶ’\n    36вҶ’---\n    37вҶ’\n    38вҶ’## Pattern 2: Polish Preposition `ze` Triggers Garbled-Word False Positive\n    39вҶ’\n    40вҶ’**Affected files:** Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…, Konfitury ze Liwek.\n    41вҶ’\n    42вҶ’**Why it fails:** The `isLikelyGarbled` multi-word check flags any short (вүӨ2 letter) lowercase word that is not in `commonShort2`. The set `commonShort2` contains `\"z\"` (common Polish preposition) but NOT `\"ze\"` (its form used before consonant clusters). The title `Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…` contains `ze`, which:\n    43вҶ’- starts with lowercase `z` вҶ’ `/^[a-z]/` matches\n    44вҶ’- `\"ze\".replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\")` = `\"ze\"`, length 2 вүӨ 2\n    45вҶ’- `\"ze\"` is not in `commonShort2`\n    46вҶ’\n    47вҶ’So `isLikelyGarbled(\"Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…\")` returns `true`, and `passesHardFilters` returns `false`. The actual title is entirely absent from the candidate pool. The algorithm picks something else (likely a body-text or ingredient line).\n    48вҶ’\n    49вҶ’**Concrete trace вҖ” Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…:**\n    50вҶ’```\n    51вҶ’File line 1: Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…   вҶҗ filtered out; ze not in commonShort2\n    52вҶ’File line 8: SkЕӮadniki (4-5 porcji)      вҶҗ survives, becomes best candidate\n    53вҶ’```\n    54вҶ’\n    55вҶ’---\n    56вҶ’\n    57вҶ’## Pattern 3: Two-Word Title Split Across Lines вҖ” Dedup Removes the Compound\n    58вҶ’\n    59вҶ’**Affected files:** Lamb Stew, Е»ur Е»ytni, and likely others.\n    60вҶ’\n    61вҶ’**Why it fails:** When a two-word title is split across two lines, each word becomes both a valid single-line candidate AND part of a 2-line join candidate. The dedup logic (\"keep the shorter substring\") then removes the compound join.\n    62вҶ’\n    63вҶ’**Concrete trace вҖ” Lamb Stew:**\n    64вҶ’```\n    65вҶ’File line 1: Lamb     вҶҗ single candidate: passes (4 ASCII letters, vowel ratio OK)\n    66вҶ’File line 2: Stew     вҶҗ single candidate: passes (4 ASCII letters, vowel ratio OK)\n    67вҶ’2-line join: Lamb Stew вҶҗ also generated\n    68вҶ’```\n    69вҶ’All three pass threshold. Dedup runs:\n    70вҶ’- `Lamb Stew` contains `Lamb` (shorter) вҶ’ `Lamb Stew` removed\n    71вҶ’- `Lamb Stew` contains `Stew` (shorter) вҶ’ `Lamb Stew` removed\n    72вҶ’- Result: `Lamb` and `Stew` survive вҶ’ returns `Lamb + Stew`\n    73вҶ’\n    74вҶ’Expected `Lamb Stew`. The compound title is destroyed by its own component parts.\n    75вҶ’\n    76вҶ’**Concrete trace вҖ” Е»ur Е»ytni:**\n    77вҶ’```\n    78вҶ’File line 1: Е»ur     вҶҗ isLikelyGarbled (Е» is non-ASCII, ASCII letters = \"ur\" = 2 chars, triggers single-word short rule)\n    79вҶ’File line 2: Ејytni   вҶҗ single candidate\n    80вҶ’2-line join: Е»ur Ејytni  вҶҗ generated with lowercase Еј\n    81вҶ’Expected:    Е»ur Е»ytni   вҶҗ Title Case mismatch AND the join is case-wrong\n    82вҶ’```\n    83вҶ’Additionally, `Е»ur` alone (ASCII letters = `ur`, 2 chars, not in COMMON_SHORT) is filtered as garbled. The 2-line join `Е»ur Ејytni` survives but has wrong casing on the second word, so even if returned it doesn't match.\n    84вҶ’\n    85вҶ’---\n    86вҶ’\n    87вҶ’## Pattern 4: Three-Line Title Where First Word Is a SECTION_LABEL\n    88вҶ’\n    89вҶ’**Affected files:** Zupy Zimowe Warzywne.\n    90вҶ’\n    91вҶ’**What the OCR has:**\n    92вҶ’```\n    93вҶ’Zupy\n    94вҶ’Zimowe\n    95вҶ’Warzywne\n    96вҶ’```\n    97вҶ’\n    98вҶ’**Why it fails:** `Zupy` appears in `SECTION_LABELS` (as a Polish category word meaning \"soups\"). The `buildCandidates` function skips 2-line and 3-line joins when the first line is a section label:\n    99вҶ’\n   100вҶ’```typescript\n   101вҶ’if (i + 1 < mergedLines.length && !isSectionLabel(line.text)) {\n   102вҶ’    // 2-line join only generated if first line is NOT a section label\n   103вҶ’```\n   104вҶ’\n   105вҶ’Since `isSectionLabel(\"Zupy\")` returns `true`, no join starting with `Zupy` is ever generated. The only surviving candidates are `Zimowe` (a single word, unusual English/Polish mix) and `Warzywne` (a single word). Neither matches the expected `Zupy Zimowe Warzywne`.\n   106вҶ’\n   107вҶ’The SECTION_LABELS entry is correct when `Zupy` appears as a standalone chapter header вҖ” but it incorrectly blocks reconstruction when `Zupy` is the start of a recipe title split across lines.\n   108вҶ’\n   109вҶ’---\n   110вҶ’\n   111вҶ’## Pattern 5: Long OCR Garbage Prologue Bypasses Burst Detection\n   112вҶ’\n   113вҶ’**Affected files:** Brownies, Sernik, Szarlotka, Zupa Grzybowa, Lemonade, Strawberry Shortcake, Strawberry Smoothie, Tomato Bisque, Tomato Chutney, Vegetable Stir Fry, Quick Golabki, and others.\n   114вҶ’\n   115вҶ’**Template structure:** These files start with ~28-35 lines of repeated OCR garbage instruction fragments (e.g., `ВҪ cup plus Дұ tablespoon of finely ground`, `nto a loured work counter and knead until smooth`, `Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold`), followed by the actual recipe name as a simple mixed-case word, then a generic template recipe body.\n   116вҶ’\n   117вҶ’**Why it fails:** `findBurstEnd` only skips lines that are BOTH short (< 20 chars) AND garbled. The garbage lines in these files are long (30вҖ“55 chars), so `findBurstEnd` returns 0 and all lines are processed.\n   118вҶ’\n   119вҶ’Several garbage lines pass `passesHardFilters`:\n   120вҶ’- `Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold` вҖ” starts with uppercase `B`, no period-space pattern, all short lowercase words exceed 2 chars вҶ’ passes\n   121вҶ’- `Cool completely on a wire rack before serving` вҖ” same\n   122вҶ’- `Remove from heat and stir in the cream` вҖ” same\n   123вҶ’\n   124вҶ’These become candidates. The actual title (`Szarlotka`, `Sernik`, etc.) is at ~70% through the document, gets no position bonus, and is a single uncommon Polish word. These competing candidates inflate the scoring pool and may push the real title below threshold or cause a wrong winner.\n   125вҶ’\n   126вҶ’**Concrete trace вҖ” Szarlotka:**\n   127вҶ’```\n   128вҶ’Lines 1вҖ“35:  OCR garbage (long lines, mostly pass filters)\n   129вҶ’Line 36:     Szarlotka   вҶҗ at 70% of document, no position bonus\n   130вҶ’Lines 38вҖ“56: Generic template ingredients/instructions\n   131вҶ’```\n   132вҶ’The algorithm has 20+ candidates before the title and must identify `Szarlotka` from among generic English cooking instructions. If the threshold is set by any garbage line with accidentally high embedding similarity to a recipe title, `Szarlotka` may not survive.\n   133вҶ’\n   134вҶ’---\n   135вҶ’\n   136вҶ’## Pattern 6: Season/Context Header Wins Over Mixed-Case Title\n   137вҶ’\n   138вҶ’**Affected files:** Beet Salad, Coleslaw, and similar files with `SEZON: WIOSNA` header.\n   139вҶ’\n   140вҶ’**Structure:**\n   141вҶ’```\n   142вҶ’SEZON: WIOSNA   вҶҗ line 1, ALL_CAPS, passes hard filters\n   143вҶ’[blank]\n   144вҶ’Beet Salad      вҶҗ line 3, mixed case\n   145вҶ’```\n   146вҶ’\n   147вҶ’**Why it fails:** `SEZON: WIOSNA` passes hard filters and `isStructuralHeading` check (ALL_CAPS, 2 words, both вүҘ4 letters). It gets a 0.10 structural bonus AND a 0.12 position bonus (position 0). `Beet Salad` at position 2 gets a smaller position bonus and no structural bonus. The algorithm picks `SEZON: WIOSNA`.\n   148вҶ’\n   149вҶ’The `METADATA_PATTERNS` list handles `DLA`, `SERVES`, `PREP TIME`, etc. but does not include `SEZON:` (season indicator). Seasonal recipe categorization headers like `SEZON: WIOSNA`, `SEZON: JESIEЕғ` are not recognized as metadata.\n   150вҶ’\n   151вҶ’---\n   152вҶ’\n   153вҶ’## Pattern 7: Parenthetical English Subtitles Over-Merged Into Title\n   154вҶ’\n   155вҶ’**Affected files:** Piernik, Е»urek, Pierogi Ruskie, Bigos MyЕӣliwski, Makowiec.\n   156вҶ’\n   157вҶ’**What the OCR has:**\n   158вҶ’```\n   159вҶ’PIEROGI RUSKIE\n   160вҶ’(Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)\n   161вҶ’```\n   162вҶ’or:\n   163вҶ’```\n   164вҶ’MAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake)   вҶҗ already on one line\n   165вҶ’```\n   166вҶ’\n   167вҶ’**Why it fails:** The continuation pre-merge step merges any line starting with `(` into the preceding line (designed for `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`). This incorrectly merges English subtitle glosses.\n   168вҶ’\n   169вҶ’Result: `PIEROGI RUSKIE (Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)` becomes the candidate instead of `PIEROGI RUSKIE`. The expected is `Pierogi Ruskie`. Two problems: ALL_CAPS mismatch AND parenthetical inclusion.\n   170вҶ’\n   171вҶ’For single-line cases (`MAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake)`), `isAllCaps` returns `false` (the parenthetical content is mixed case), so the line doesn't qualify as a structural heading, and the full string including the gloss is returned as a mixed-case title вҖ” while `Makowiec` alone is expected.\n   172вҶ’\n   173вҶ’---\n   174вҶ’\n   175вҶ’## Pattern 8: Compound Title Destroyed by Dedup via Substring\n   176вҶ’\n   177вҶ’**Affected file:** HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION.\n   178вҶ’\n   179вҶ’**Structure:**\n   180вҶ’```\n   181вҶ’HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION  вҶҗ line 1 (compound title)\n   182вҶ’[blank]\n   183вҶ’HERB BAKED SALMON                          вҶҗ line 3 (first sub-recipe header)\n   184вҶ’...\n   185вҶ’DILL SAUCE VARIATION                       вҶҗ line 32 (second sub-recipe header)\n   186вҶ’```\n   187вҶ’\n   188вҶ’**Why it fails:** `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` at line 1 is the correct answer. All three ALL_CAPS candidates survive threshold. The continuation logic correctly identifies `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` as `firstStructuralHeading`. The prefix-removal step correctly removes `HERB BAKED SALMON`. However, `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` (position 32) also survives.\n   189вҶ’\n   190вҶ’Dedup then runs on `[HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION, DILL SAUCE VARIATION]`:\n   191вҶ’- `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` **contains** `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` (shorter)\n   192вҶ’- вҶ’ The longer compound title is removed; only `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` survives\n   193вҶ’\n   194вҶ’The dedup rule \"keep the shorter\" is correct in general but breaks when the compound line-1 title literally contains a later sub-recipe section header as a substring.\n   195вҶ’\n   196вҶ’---\n   197вҶ’\n   198вҶ’## Minor Patterns\n   199вҶ’\n   200вҶ’### Pattern 9: Page Number Prefix Blocks Title Line\n   201вҶ’**File:** Berry Jam.\n   202вҶ’\n   203вҶ’OCR line 3: `34  Berry Jam`. The `startsWithNumber` check matches (line begins with digit `3`). The entire line is discarded. `Berry Jam` never appears as a standalone candidate.\n   204вҶ’\n   205вҶ’### Pattern 10: OCR Character Substitution in Title\n   206вҶ’**File:** CrГЁme BrГ»lГ©e.\n   207вҶ’\n   208вҶ’OCR line 1: `CrГЁme BrГ»1Г©e` (digit `1` substituted for letter `l`). The algorithm returns the corrupted OCR string. Expected: `CrГЁme BrГ»lГ©e`. The algorithm does no character-substitution correction.\n   209вҶ’\n   210вҶ’### Pattern 11: Missing Word in OCR Split Title\n   211вҶ’**File:** Bigos z Wdzonych Kielbas.\n   212вҶ’\n   213вҶ’OCR: `Bigos` (line 1) + `Wdzonych Kielbas` (line 2). The preposition `z` is absent from the OCR. The 2-line join produces `Bigos Wdzonych Kielbas`. Expected: `Bigos z Wdzonych Kielbas`. An OCR omission that cannot be recovered without external knowledge.\n   214вҶ’\n   215вҶ’---\n   216вҶ’\n   217вҶ’## Common Themes\n   218вҶ’\n   219вҶ’### 1. No case normalization\n   220вҶ’The algorithm treats OCR casing as ground truth. Roughly a third of failures are pure ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatches where the algorithm found the right title content but returned it in the wrong case. Adding a normalization pass (e.g., Title Case for mixed-alpha strings, preserve ALL_CAPS only when all non-trivial words are вүҘ5 chars or it's a known-ALL-CAPS pattern) would eliminate the largest single failure cluster.\n   221вҶ’\n   222вҶ’### 2. The garbled-word filter is too aggressive for non-ASCII short words\n   223вҶ’`ze`, and potentially other valid 2-letter tokens in languages with non-ASCII characters, are treated as garbage because the `commonShort2` set is ASCII-English-centric and the `[a-z]` regex only matches ASCII. Words like `ze`, `bo`, `ni`, `tu` are legitimate Polish words/prepositions but all fail the filter. The fix is to add Polish short prepositions to `commonShort2` (at minimum: `ze`, `bo`, `na`, `ni`, `po`, `ku`).\n   224вҶ’\n   225вҶ’### 3. The burst-detection threshold (< 20 chars) is too narrow\n   226вҶ’Long repeated OCR garbage lines bypass `findBurstEnd` because they exceed 20 characters. The burst detection should also recognize long repeated lines (appearing вүҘ2 times before the first likely title candidate) as garbage preamble. Alternatively, a repeated-line filter (any line appearing вүҘ3 times in the document is noise) would handle these template-garbage files.\n   227вҶ’\n   228вҶ’### 4. The \"shorter wins\" dedup rule and the \"section labels block joins\" rule each have known exceptions\n   229вҶ’- The dedup rule breaks when a compound title on line 1 contains a later sub-recipe header as a literal substring (HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION).\n   230вҶ’- The section-label join-block rule breaks when a category word (`Zupy`, potentially `Placki`) starts a multi-line recipe title rather than standing alone as a category.\n   231вҶ’\n   232вҶ’These two rules are already annotated in the code as sensitive (\"DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC\"), so any fix should be targeted rather than broad.\n   233вҶ’\n   234вҶ’### 5. Continuation pre-merge is too aggressive with `(`\n   235вҶ’The `(` continuation character is designed for recipe variant suffixes like `(VARIATION D)`. It also matches English subtitle glosses like `(Polish Gingerbread)` and `(Hunter's Stew)`. A simple guard вҖ” don't merge `(` continuations when the preceding line is already a complete multi-word title вҖ” would prevent most cases in Pattern 7.\n   236вҶ’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"170bdbf7-3568-4ea7-9b3d-3d7e36d78c47","uuid":"c727f2a6-bc02-4d3d-be00-e41f389bd343","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/feedback.md","content":"# Iteration 18 вҖ” Failure Analysis\n\n## Overview\n\n54 failures out of 203 test cases (73% pass rate). The failures cluster into 8 distinct root-cause patterns. Most failures involve one of two dominant issues: **ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatch** (algorithm faithfully returns OCR casing but test expects canonical mixed case) and **OCR garbage prologue that bypasses burst detection** (long garbage lines sneak through and beat the real title). Several other structural bugs account for the remainder.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 1: ALL_CAPS Title in OCR, Mixed-Case Expected (largest group, ~20 failures)\n\n**Affected files:** Barszcz, Beef Stew, Mushroom Pasta, Mushroom Barley Soup, Kluski ЕҡlД…skie, Pierogi Ruskie, Placki Serowe, Placki Ziemniaczane, Placki Owocowe, Placki SЕӮodkie, Roladki Szpinakowe, Paella Valenciana, Chocolate Brownies + Fudgy Chocolate Brownies, and others.\n\n**What the OCR has:** The recipe title is in ALL_CAPS (e.g., `BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`, `MUSHROOM PASTA`, `PLACKI SEROWE`).\n\n**What the algorithm returns:** The verbatim OCR string in ALL_CAPS (e.g., `BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`).\n\n**What the test expects:** Title-cased string (e.g., `Barszcz`, `Beef Stew`, `Placki Serowe`).\n\n**Why it fails:** The algorithm has no case normalization step. It returns text exactly as it appears in the OCR. Tests that have ALL_CAPS expectations (e.g., `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA`, `ARAYES SHRAK`) pass because the expected string matches the OCR. Tests with Title Case expectations fail because the expected string differs in case.\n\n**Concrete trace вҖ” Barszcz:**\n```\nFile line 1: BARSZCZ\nExpected:    Barszcz\nGot:         BARSZCZ\n```\n`BARSZCZ` is a valid single-word structural candidate. It passes all hard filters and scores well for recipe title. The algorithm returns it faithfully. The test fails on a string-equality comparison.\n\n**Concrete trace вҖ” Paella Valenciana:**\n```\nFile line 1: PAELLA\nFile line 2: VALENCIANA\n```\nBoth are ALL_CAPS single-word lines (вүӨ2 words, вүӨ25 chars). The caps-coalescing logic correctly merges them into `PAELLA VALENCIANA`. But expected is `Paella Valenciana`. Case mismatch.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 2: Polish Preposition `ze` Triggers Garbled-Word False Positive\n\n**Affected files:** Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…, Konfitury ze Liwek.\n\n**Why it fails:** The `isLikelyGarbled` multi-word check flags any short (вүӨ2 letter) lowercase word that is not in `commonShort2`. The set `commonShort2` contains `\"z\"` (common Polish preposition) but NOT `\"ze\"` (its form used before consonant clusters). The title `Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…` contains `ze`, which:\n- starts with lowercase `z` вҶ’ `/^[a-z]/` matches\n- `\"ze\".replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\")` = `\"ze\"`, length 2 вүӨ 2\n- `\"ze\"` is not in `commonShort2`\n\nSo `isLikelyGarbled(\"Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…\")` returns `true`, and `passesHardFilters` returns `false`. The actual title is entirely absent from the candidate pool. The algorithm picks something else (likely a body-text or ingredient line).\n\n**Concrete trace вҖ” Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…:**\n```\nFile line 1: Krem Grzybowy ze ЕҡmietanД…   вҶҗ filtered out; ze not in commonShort2\nFile line 8: SkЕӮadniki (4-5 porcji)      вҶҗ survives, becomes best candidate\n```\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 3: Two-Word Title Split Across Lines вҖ” Dedup Removes the Compound\n\n**Affected files:** Lamb Stew, Е»ur Е»ytni, and likely others.\n\n**Why it fails:** When a two-word title is split across two lines, each word becomes both a valid single-line candidate AND part of a 2-line join candidate. The dedup logic (\"keep the shorter substring\") then removes the compound join.\n\n**Concrete trace вҖ” Lamb Stew:**\n```\nFile line 1: Lamb     вҶҗ single candidate: passes (4 ASCII letters, vowel ratio OK)\nFile line 2: Stew     вҶҗ single candidate: passes (4 ASCII letters, vowel ratio OK)\n2-line join: Lamb Stew вҶҗ also generated\n```\nAll three pass threshold. Dedup runs:\n- `Lamb Stew` contains `Lamb` (shorter) вҶ’ `Lamb Stew` removed\n- `Lamb Stew` contains `Stew` (shorter) вҶ’ `Lamb Stew` removed\n- Result: `Lamb` and `Stew` survive вҶ’ returns `Lamb + Stew`\n\nExpected `Lamb Stew`. The compound title is destroyed by its own component parts.\n\n**Concrete trace вҖ” Е»ur Е»ytni:**\n```\nFile line 1: Е»ur     вҶҗ isLikelyGarbled (Е» is non-ASCII, ASCII letters = \"ur\" = 2 chars, triggers single-word short rule)\nFile line 2: Ејytni   вҶҗ single candidate\n2-line join: Е»ur Ејytni  вҶҗ generated with lowercase Еј\nExpected:    Е»ur Е»ytni   вҶҗ Title Case mismatch AND the join is case-wrong\n```\nAdditionally, `Е»ur` alone (ASCII letters = `ur`, 2 chars, not in COMMON_SHORT) is filtered as garbled. The 2-line join `Е»ur Ејytni` survives but has wrong casing on the second word, so even if returned it doesn't match.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 4: Three-Line Title Where First Word Is a SECTION_LABEL\n\n**Affected files:** Zupy Zimowe Warzywne.\n\n**What the OCR has:**\n```\nZupy\nZimowe\nWarzywne\n```\n\n**Why it fails:** `Zupy` appears in `SECTION_LABELS` (as a Polish category word meaning \"soups\"). The `buildCandidates` function skips 2-line and 3-line joins when the first line is a section label:\n\n```typescript\nif (i + 1 < mergedLines.length && !isSectionLabel(line.text)) {\n    // 2-line join only generated if first line is NOT a section label\n```\n\nSince `isSectionLabel(\"Zupy\")` returns `true`, no join starting with `Zupy` is ever generated. The only surviving candidates are `Zimowe` (a single word, unusual English/Polish mix) and `Warzywne` (a single word). Neither matches the expected `Zupy Zimowe Warzywne`.\n\nThe SECTION_LABELS entry is correct when `Zupy` appears as a standalone chapter header вҖ” but it incorrectly blocks reconstruction when `Zupy` is the start of a recipe title split across lines.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 5: Long OCR Garbage Prologue Bypasses Burst Detection\n\n**Affected files:** Brownies, Sernik, Szarlotka, Zupa Grzybowa, Lemonade, Strawberry Shortcake, Strawberry Smoothie, Tomato Bisque, Tomato Chutney, Vegetable Stir Fry, Quick Golabki, and others.\n\n**Template structure:** These files start with ~28-35 lines of repeated OCR garbage instruction fragments (e.g., `ВҪ cup plus Дұ tablespoon of finely ground`, `nto a loured work counter and knead until smooth`, `Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold`), followed by the actual recipe name as a simple mixed-case word, then a generic template recipe body.\n\n**Why it fails:** `findBurstEnd` only skips lines that are BOTH short (< 20 chars) AND garbled. The garbage lines in these files are long (30вҖ“55 chars), so `findBurstEnd` returns 0 and all lines are processed.\n\nSeveral garbage lines pass `passesHardFilters`:\n- `Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold` вҖ” starts with uppercase `B`, no period-space pattern, all short lowercase words exceed 2 chars вҶ’ passes\n- `Cool completely on a wire rack before serving` вҖ” same\n- `Remove from heat and stir in the cream` вҖ” same\n\nThese become candidates. The actual title (`Szarlotka`, `Sernik`, etc.) is at ~70% through the document, gets no position bonus, and is a single uncommon Polish word. These competing candidates inflate the scoring pool and may push the real title below threshold or cause a wrong winner.\n\n**Concrete trace вҖ” Szarlotka:**\n```\nLines 1вҖ“35:  OCR garbage (long lines, mostly pass filters)\nLine 36:     Szarlotka   вҶҗ at 70% of document, no position bonus\nLines 38вҖ“56: Generic template ingredients/instructions\n```\nThe algorithm has 20+ candidates before the title and must identify `Szarlotka` from among generic English cooking instructions. If the threshold is set by any garbage line with accidentally high embedding similarity to a recipe title, `Szarlotka` may not survive.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 6: Season/Context Header Wins Over Mixed-Case Title\n\n**Affected files:** Beet Salad, Coleslaw, and similar files with `SEZON: WIOSNA` header.\n\n**Structure:**\n```\nSEZON: WIOSNA   вҶҗ line 1, ALL_CAPS, passes hard filters\n[blank]\nBeet Salad      вҶҗ line 3, mixed case\n```\n\n**Why it fails:** `SEZON: WIOSNA` passes hard filters and `isStructuralHeading` check (ALL_CAPS, 2 words, both вүҘ4 letters). It gets a 0.10 structural bonus AND a 0.12 position bonus (position 0). `Beet Salad` at position 2 gets a smaller position bonus and no structural bonus. The algorithm picks `SEZON: WIOSNA`.\n\nThe `METADATA_PATTERNS` list handles `DLA`, `SERVES`, `PREP TIME`, etc. but does not include `SEZON:` (season indicator). Seasonal recipe categorization headers like `SEZON: WIOSNA`, `SEZON: JESIEЕғ` are not recognized as metadata.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 7: Parenthetical English Subtitles Over-Merged Into Title\n\n**Affected files:** Piernik, Е»urek, Pierogi Ruskie, Bigos MyЕӣliwski, Makowiec.\n\n**What the OCR has:**\n```\nPIEROGI RUSKIE\n(Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)\n```\nor:\n```\nMAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake)   вҶҗ already on one line\n```\n\n**Why it fails:** The continuation pre-merge step merges any line starting with `(` into the preceding line (designed for `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`). This incorrectly merges English subtitle glosses.\n\nResult: `PIEROGI RUSKIE (Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)` becomes the candidate instead of `PIEROGI RUSKIE`. The expected is `Pierogi Ruskie`. Two problems: ALL_CAPS mismatch AND parenthetical inclusion.\n\nFor single-line cases (`MAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake)`), `isAllCaps` returns `false` (the parenthetical content is mixed case), so the line doesn't qualify as a structural heading, and the full string including the gloss is returned as a mixed-case title вҖ” while `Makowiec` alone is expected.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 8: Compound Title Destroyed by Dedup via Substring\n\n**Affected file:** HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION.\n\n**Structure:**\n```\nHERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION  вҶҗ line 1 (compound title)\n[blank]\nHERB BAKED SALMON                          вҶҗ line 3 (first sub-recipe header)\n...\nDILL SAUCE VARIATION                       вҶҗ line 32 (second sub-recipe header)\n```\n\n**Why it fails:** `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` at line 1 is the correct answer. All three ALL_CAPS candidates survive threshold. The continuation logic correctly identifies `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` as `firstStructuralHeading`. The prefix-removal step correctly removes `HERB BAKED SALMON`. However, `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` (position 32) also survives.\n\nDedup then runs on `[HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION, DILL SAUCE VARIATION]`:\n- `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` **contains** `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` (shorter)\n- вҶ’ The longer compound title is removed; only `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` survives\n\nThe dedup rule \"keep the shorter\" is correct in general but breaks when the compound line-1 title literally contains a later sub-recipe section header as a substring.\n\n---\n\n## Minor Patterns\n\n### Pattern 9: Page Number Prefix Blocks Title Line\n**File:** Berry Jam.\n\nOCR line 3: `34  Berry Jam`. The `startsWithNumber` check matches (line begins with digit `3`). The entire line is discarded. `Berry Jam` never appears as a standalone candidate.\n\n### Pattern 10: OCR Character Substitution in Title\n**File:** CrГЁme BrГ»lГ©e.\n\nOCR line 1: `CrГЁme BrГ»1Г©e` (digit `1` substituted for letter `l`). The algorithm returns the corrupted OCR string. Expected: `CrГЁme BrГ»lГ©e`. The algorithm does no character-substitution correction.\n\n### Pattern 11: Missing Word in OCR Split Title\n**File:** Bigos z Wdzonych Kielbas.\n\nOCR: `Bigos` (line 1) + `Wdzonych Kielbas` (line 2). The preposition `z` is absent from the OCR. The 2-line join produces `Bigos Wdzonych Kielbas`. Expected: `Bigos z Wdzonych Kielbas`. An OCR omission that cannot be recovered without external knowledge.\n\n---\n\n## Common Themes\n\n### 1. No case normalization\nThe algorithm treats OCR casing as ground truth. Roughly a third of failures are pure ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatches where the algorithm found the right title content but returned it in the wrong case. Adding a normalization pass (e.g., Title Case for mixed-alpha strings, preserve ALL_CAPS only when all non-trivial words are вүҘ5 chars or it's a known-ALL-CAPS pattern) would eliminate the largest single failure cluster.\n\n### 2. The garbled-word filter is too aggressive for non-ASCII short words\n`ze`, and potentially other valid 2-letter tokens in languages with non-ASCII characters, are treated as garbage because the `commonShort2` set is ASCII-English-centric and the `[a-z]` regex only matches ASCII. Words like `ze`, `bo`, `ni`, `tu` are legitimate Polish words/prepositions but all fail the filter. The fix is to add Polish short prepositions to `commonShort2` (at minimum: `ze`, `bo`, `na`, `ni`, `po`, `ku`).\n\n### 3. The burst-detection threshold (< 20 chars) is too narrow\nLong repeated OCR garbage lines bypass `findBurstEnd` because they exceed 20 characters. The burst detection should also recognize long repeated lines (appearing вүҘ2 times before the first likely title candidate) as garbage preamble. Alternatively, a repeated-line filter (any line appearing вүҘ3 times in the document is noise) would handle these template-garbage files.\n\n### 4. The \"shorter wins\" dedup rule and the \"section labels block joins\" rule each have known exceptions\n- The dedup rule breaks when a compound title on line 1 contains a later sub-recipe header as a literal substring (HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION).\n- The section-label join-block rule breaks when a category word (`Zupy`, potentially `Placki`) starts a multi-line recipe title rather than standing alone as a category.\n\nThese two rules are already annotated in the code as sensitive (\"DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC\"), so any fix should be targeted rather than broad.\n\n### 5. Continuation pre-merge is too aggressive with `(`\nThe `(` continuation character is designed for recipe variant suffixes like `(VARIATION D)`. It also matches English subtitle glosses like `(Polish Gingerbread)` and `(Hunter's Stew)`. A simple guard вҖ” don't merge `(` continuations when the preceding line is already a complete multi-word title вҖ” would prevent most cases in Pattern 7.\n","numLines":236,"startLine":1,"totalLines":236}}}
